        <td>AFFO</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>10</td>
        <td>Shares outstanding (million)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>$5</td>
        <td>AFFO / share</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>14Ã—</td>
        <td>Property subsector average P/AFFO multiple</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
  <p>Applying the office subsector average P/AFFP multiple of 14Ã— yield a value per share of $55 Ã— 14 = $70
The REIT share value using the price-to-AFFO approach is thus $70</p>

  <h3 id="approach-4-value-of-reit-share-using-discounted-cash-flow-approach">Approach 4: Value of REIT share using discounted cash flow approach</h3>

  <p>|          | 2014  | 2015  | 2016  |
|â€”â€”â€”-|â€”â€”-|â€”â€”-|â€”â€”-|
| Dividend | $5.00 | $5.10 | $5.20 |
Present value in 2016 of dividends stream beginning in 2017 = 5.20 ( 1 + 1% ) / ( 0.09 - 0.01 ) = 65.65
These dividends are discounted at rate of 9%.
Value of a REIT share = PV (dividends for years 1 through n) + PV (terminal value at the end of year n)
= PV<sub> 2014 dividend</sub> + PV<sub> 2015 dividend</sub> + PV<sub> 2016 dividend</sub> + PV<sub> 2017 and later dividends (terminal value)</sub>
= $5.00/1.09 + $5.10/1.09<sup>2</sup> + $5.20/1.09<sup>3</sup> + $65.65/1.09<sup>3</sup> =$63.59
The REIT share value using the discounted cash flow approach is thus $63.59</p>
</blockquote>

